China Stocks: FAW, Shanghai Zhixin, Sinovel, Wuliangye, Yanzhou

-- B y   B l o o m b e r g   N e w s
-- 
2011-04-27T08:24:43Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-04-26/faw-hebei-iron-jiangxi-copper-sinovel-china-equity-preview.html
The following companies had unusual
price changes in  China  trading. Stock symbols are in parentheses
and share prices are as of the 3 p.m. close.  The Shanghai Composite Index, which tracks the bigger of
China’s stock exchanges, dropped 13.6 points, or 0.5 percent, to
2,925.41. The  CSI 300 Index (SHSZ300)  slid 0.7 percent to 3,209.50.  China State Construction Engineering Corp. (601668 CH), the
nation’s largest construction company, advanced 1.3 percent to
4.01 yuan. The company won nine contracts worth a total of 37.2
billion yuan, according to a statement to the Shanghai Stock
Exchange today.  FAW Car Co. (000800 CH) slid 4.4 percent to 15.41 yuan, the
biggest loss since Jan. 17. The carmaker’s first-quarter net
income fell 44 percent from a year earlier to 391.5 million
yuan, the company said in a statement to the Shenzhen Stock
Exchange.  Norinco International Cooperation Ltd. (000065)  (000065 CH) surged
by the 10 percent daily limit to 20.74 yuan. The company made a
net profit of 4.8 million yuan in the first quarter, compared
with a loss of 15.7 million yuan a year earlier, according to a
statement to the Shenzhen Stock Exchange yesterday.  Shanghai Zhixin Electric Co. (600517 CH), an electric
equipment maker, plunged 7.6 percent to 13.56 yuan, the biggest
loss since May 12. The company’s first-quarter profit declined
42 percent to 30.7 million yuan, according to a statement to the
Shanghai Stock Exchange yesterday.  Sinovel Wind Group Co. (601558 CH), China’s largest wind-
turbine maker, lost 4.9 percent to 65.82 yuan, the lowest close
since its listing on Jan. 13. The company’s profit growth slowed
to 1 percent in the first quarter, according to a statement to
the  Shanghai Stock Exchange  yesterday.  Wuliangye Yibin Co. (000858 CH), China’s second-biggest
maker of white liquor by market value, climbed 2.6 percent to
32.48 yuan. Citigroup Inc. recommended investors “overweight”
consumer staples producers in a report yesterday, citing factors
including rising income growth among farmers.  Yanzhou Coal Mining Co. (600188 CH) advanced 1.2 percent to
34.26 yuan. The company’s first-quarter profit increased 18
percent to 2.48 billion yuan, according to a statement to the
Hong Kong stock exchange yesterday.  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
Darren Boey at 
 dboey@bloomberg.net  